02:34.657 --> 02:41.691
The other question would have to do with your early 
teaching skin in this country. You said you were

02:41.711 --> 02:46.420
teaching people who were with the Sierra Club and 
wanted to know how to get back to their cabins. Were

02:46.440 --> 02:50.569
these people who you taught one-on-one, or did you 
have masking classes of people? What was that

02:50.649 --> 02:51.771
like? A variety. Anything from one-on-one that's 
private lessons to 30, like every Easter, the

02:54.645 --> 03:05.254
board of directors would come up with their 
children. tiny tots up and bring their children

03:06.044 --> 03:15.515
over the Easter weekend and just dump them on me so 
that they could go skiing somewhere else. And I had

03:15.535 --> 03:20.801
these thirty kids for four or five years, 
probably. And I became, they were so thrilled with

03:20.821 --> 03:23.704
their progress. And I had a little race at the end of 
the week, of the Easter week, which we were putting

03:24.104 --> 03:33.435
the poles in a triangle and they had to go under it 
because that's what we were doing as kids. and see

03:33.415 --> 03:36.017
all the things that we were doing when I was 
teaching. And they loved it. And that's where this

03:37.559 --> 03:45.046
gal, Shafi, was in that class and later became an 
Olympic skier. Several of those kids made it to

03:45.246 --> 04:02.983
Dartmouth and to, yeah, onto the Olympic team 
because I met the lady of the president of the

03:45.246 --> 04:02.983
Sierra Club, lived in Berkeley, and I visited her. 
In fact, I was invited to her daughter's wedding,

04:03.217 --> 04:08.825
and I just feel terrible because I never gave her a 
present. I didn't have any money. I was invited to

04:09.706 --> 04:13.431
her daughter's present. She was also in that 
class.

04:17.677 --> 04:20.761
Yes, I think Dorothy Leonard. Jean, Dorothy, 
something like that. Leonard. Dick Leonard is the

04:23.585 --> 04:29.433
president of this year of this chapter, or maybe 
the national, I don't know. But he was an attorney.

04:31.786 --> 04:49.710
and lived in the Berkeley Hills, in a lovely home 
overlooking the bay, and they would gather up and

04:31.786 --> 04:49.710
they thought, the world of me, how marvelous, and 
the kids all love me, you know, and they became

04:31.786 --> 04:49.710
champions in their own right after that, giving 
him a good foundation, fun, Control,

04:49.943 --> 04:52.629
coordination, the fundamentals. What was your 
teaching style? Did you stick with the techniques

04:54.393 --> 04:59.485
a lot, or did you stop and tell jokes and stories in 
between? The whole thing. I believe in the whole

05:00.828 --> 05:03.514
thing. Maintain, get their attention and hold it, 
and you can only hold it by a variety of things

05:03.832 --> 05:12.880
instead of harping on one thing. You wanted to 
mention the same kind of relationship activities

05:12.900 --> 05:17.665
with Junior Davis. I did the same thing in APTIS. I 
had Junior Davis come volunteer. Volunteer.

05:23.590 --> 05:30.717
Volunteer to, came, a question came through from 
the, from the main, tennis association from San

05:30.697 --> 05:46.123
Francisco if I would start a Junior Davis

05:30.697 --> 05:46.123
Cup team in my area there, and I accepted the 
assignment. Mark was there, and I hired several,

05:46.677 --> 05:57.955
two or three local guys, Mark, to help me, and we 
had, oh God, how many, 40, 50 kids, boys and girls.

05:58.376 --> 06:03.103
And you took a program to, a similar program to 
Watsonville? Yes, I had a similar program,

06:03.124 --> 06:14.001
because a lady, the principal of a school from 
Watsonville, turned out to be a former national

06:03.124 --> 06:14.001
champion. Barbara Hedlund, a ranked player. And 
she found out about this club that we started. This

06:22.084 --> 06:30.557
was kind of a community that was not really into 
sports very much until Gina and I got in there. They

06:30.577 --> 06:34.063
had a little, but we really got it going. And 
Barbara Hedlund, they came kind of out of the

06:34.083 --> 06:38.871
woodwork, all these people that had been 
semi-retired. It was a retirement community,

06:38.891 --> 06:42.216
actually. She and I played doubles together, and 
we beat everybody. I mean, we could have gone on and

06:45.895 --> 06:54.898
gotten our own national ranking, but she had 
personal problems with her husband. And she and I

06:54.918 --> 06:57.825
would just scream at her. But that would have put 
you in a bad position because you would have gotten

06:58.312 --> 07:00.976
too much visibility. It would have been national 
publicity again. It was probably a good thing that

07:02.498 --> 07:05.803
whatever problems she had kept you from doing it. 
She was in national women's levels. Yeah, she was

07:07.746 --> 07:09.509
national. Yeah, she was already ranked. But her 
school, she asked if I would run a tennis program in

07:12.193 --> 07:23.830
Watsonville for her school after ours, which I 
did. You were single all that time. How did you

07:25.999 --> 07:27.942
spend your time when you weren't? No, no. Oh, okay. 
Before that then, backing up to the point that you

07:29.945 --> 07:40.299
were still single with the skiing and all, how did 
you spend your time when you weren't teaching?

07:40.319 --> 07:49.412
Well, usually looking for girls and food, good 
restaurants to eat because I didn't know how to

07:40.319 --> 07:49.412
cook. read, and usually girl watching, and maybe 
going to a dance here and there. So you go to public

07:56.661 --> 08:01.447
places a lot. Public places, and then would get 
involved with my own projects. I'd make up

08:04.972 --> 08:16.108
projects and involve myself unknowingly, like 
making movies, getting an 8mm camera and I

08:17.422 --> 08:23.711
discovered a flaw in my backhand in those days and 
straightened that out. I got myself a new backhand

08:23.752 --> 08:28.919
by taking movies, taking movies of all the top 
players. I have movies of

08:29.039 --> 08:36.531
guys that are now on television. Tony Trabert, his 
partner Talbert who runs the who was the

08:42.565 --> 08:45.688
tournament director for the U.S. Open in New York 
City. All these guys, they have movies. I studied

08:47.991 --> 08:51.154
all their technique. So I got in these, and I made 
ski movies. I found a girl that she always kids me

08:58.863 --> 09:05.410
about because she looks older than she is. She kept 
showing up in these movies, good-looking, and she

09:05.770 --> 09:10.075
was a little Jewish girl about... no more than 15 
years old, very good-looking and radiant. Can I

09:16.221 --> 09:19.524
tell a quick anecdote about that movie and that 
girl? As I indicated, he had never told me very much

09:20.145 --> 09:27.772
of anything, and would shy a hedge on any questions 
about relationships. So right after we got the job

09:28.132 --> 09:43.285
as the pro at Beaver's Racquet, the first pro 
tennis pro job in Santa Cruz County, and we started

09:28.132 --> 09:43.285
generating some social activities around this 
little membership project. One of the things we

09:43.265 --> 09:53.398
did would be to have a mixed doubles night and then 
everybody would bring a jug of wine and we'd have

09:43.265 --> 09:53.398
some food and sit around and socialize. And he 
decided he wanted to show some of these little

09:53.418 --> 09:57.884
skate movies, which I had not seen. So I'm helping 
him. We're getting the projector out and all of a

09:59.025 --> 10:06.555
sudden up here on the screen, it's repeating this 
picture of him with this girl somewhere in the

10:06.974 --> 10:16.246
group or together with her and the whole crowd and I 
really crack up because I said, who is that woman?

10:16.266 --> 10:18.069
And I've introduced other females. You see, I 
broke the rule. You see? And it can only cause

10:21.594 --> 10:23.216
trouble. It never turns out right. And her name was 
Wolf. I can't think of her name, but her name was

10:27.842 --> 10:32.008
Wolf, spelled W-O-L-F-F. Very young girl who full 
of enthusiasm for my project. She was actually

10:38.852 --> 10:41.316
volunteered to be an assistant. What are we going 
to do today, Dennis, type of thing. Show up at your

10:44.720 --> 10:46.443
door. What are we going to shoot today? What story? 
So she was a perfect foil partner for me to get

10:50.868 --> 11:05.668
involved in other projects and have a marvelous 
time making movies, which I showed on Saturday

10:50.868 --> 11:05.668
nights to hundreds of people. instructional 
movies, cartoons. They would come up, okay, let's

11:10.349 --> 11:12.652
make a cartoon. She'd make a clown costume for me so 
that I could play the clown. I would make skis out of

11:20.324 --> 11:34.626
barrel pieces, staves, nail old shoes to it so I 
could ski backwards and things like that and fall

11:20.324 --> 11:34.626
down and all the audience would just roar, you 
know? And I had bought a recorder, and I remember

11:35.112 --> 11:46.752
the songs I recorded as background music to the ski 
movies. Pergin Suite makes a marvelous downhill

11:46.872 --> 11:50.859
race. I filmed the Silver Belt, famous race of 
Trigger Boat, every year with some of the top

11:51.420 --> 11:58.652
racers in it. Did you watch a lot of movies, Lee 
Camp? Yeah, as many as we got, these Hollywood

12:02.416 --> 12:05.525
movies. Marvelous, free movies. Can't beat that. 
Did any of them stick with you? I can't think of one

12:12.440 --> 12:24.075
offhand, but you've got to know the movie stars 
that kept coming back, the faces, and the

12:12.440 --> 12:24.075
Hollywood productions were great. We didn't see 
any other, not one camp incident that you read

12:24.396 --> 12:28.941
about. They showed us the horror movies that I know 
of of these concentration camps. We never saw one

12:34.629 --> 12:36.691
of those. So we were nothing but good front movies 
playing there. We veered away from Ms. Wolf

12:41.971 --> 12:45.296
successfully. Is there anything about, you can 
say, look, I don't know anything about Wolf.

12:50.525 --> 12:51.186
Nothing whatsoever. I considered her much too 
young. Just because she looked mature and acted

12:55.192 --> 12:58.698
mature, she wasn't. She did take me to meet their 
parents in San Francisco. and they turned out to,

13:03.925 --> 13:08.290
they were engaged in some kind of political thing, 
I could tell. There was something going on, and I

13:08.490 --> 13:12.375
didn't really want to get involved. He was a 
professor of some sort at the time. It was during

13:14.297 --> 13:18.843
the era that all of the... What, McCarthyism? 
Might have been, might have been. I just, and

13:20.805 --> 13:23.248
that's only just guesswork. They were involved in 
some books and paper and all this intellectual

13:23.268 --> 13:31.097
stuff, and laying around, and here's this young, 
girl, you know, introducing me, and I believe we

13:31.432 --> 13:43.627
had dinner, and she must have told him that she had a 
lot of fun up at the Sierra Club with this guy, you

13:31.432 --> 13:43.627
know, making movies. I would assume that's the way 
to open it up. But I'm sure... If you had joined a

13:49.934 --> 13:52.818
political party, what party would you have 
joined? None. Do you feel yourself, if someone

13:54.840 --> 13:57.844
says... Yeah, the Republicans are doing this and 
that. Do you feel more akin? Yeah, I have. Someone

14:03.676 --> 14:05.641
says the Democrats are doing this and that. You 
say, gee, I would support that. Yeah, I do. I do feel

14:10.691 --> 14:13.437
about issues. something that was unknown, this 
terminology. In fact, I had a conversation with my

14:16.740 --> 14:27.351
niece as I was reading these, since I started 
reading some German newspaper that says, they

14:16.740 --> 14:27.351
still don't know how to write published 
newspapers. All they can talk about is, first of

14:27.992 --> 14:32.076
all, their words are too long. Nobody can 
understand them. And she agreed, yeah, that their

14:34.399 --> 14:37.382
sight is a, a terrible newspaper. No, it doesn't 
have to go on. No, okay. Because the words are too

14:42.074 --> 14:43.596
long. And they never have any issues. Where is the 
issue? They're looking for issues. And then get

14:48.943 --> 14:51.966
the different sides to the issue. What they have is 
a Gespräch, which is an interview. That is a one

14:56.452 --> 14:57.794
side. Well, where in the hell is the other side? Or 
what other? You know, where is the... A Gespräch is

15:02.259 --> 15:05.563
a pretty... Well, it's not a good tool to enlighten 
people. It's okay. I may be interested in what a

15:11.150 --> 15:16.798
certain person has to say, but where's the issue? 
It's the newspaper's job to dig out the issues.

15:20.143 --> 15:20.383
Yes. Which party would you find yourself with if 
you were involved in American politics? I guess

15:26.852 --> 15:30.096
I'm not going to do that. No, I don't. You're asking 
me a straight question. Just where do you... the

15:34.282 --> 15:36.224
cross-section, the ethnic thing. Very much, Gene 
and I, just without knowing, ever discussing

15:36.505 --> 15:45.496
politics prior to our marriage, we just think 
alike. One more lucky thing that happened.

15:54.287 --> 16:01.116
Let me ask you, during the times that you were a ski 
instructor, when Would the apprehension start

16:02.058 --> 16:05.504
about what you're going to do during the summer? 
About January, February, March? Are you starting

16:08.268 --> 16:10.912
to get worried about March? March, yeah. You're 
saying, I'm getting concerned. First of May is the

16:13.376 --> 16:14.318
last. I see. So first of May is the end of the season. 
Yeah. So you have to start concerning yourself

16:19.727 --> 16:22.451
with what you're going to do this summer. My God, 
how am I going to stay alive? Well, and usually I had

16:25.616 --> 16:27.880
no prospects. So I tried to save as much money, 
which wasn't very much because these jobs are

16:29.598 --> 16:41.367
low-level kind of jobs as far as money is 
concerned. Right. How would you go about

16:42.510 --> 16:45.818
preparing yourself for May 1st? I was saving as 
much as I could. And then this goes usually

16:50.597 --> 17:10.382
straight for Stockton, which is in the middle of 
the San

16:50.597 --> 17:10.382
Joaquin Valley and the agricultural community. 
So if worse came to worse, if I didn't plan to come up

17:10.402 --> 17:16.530
with anything, then I'd just jump on the truck at 5 
o'clock in the morning and go out to wherever we

17:10.402 --> 17:16.530
were, find a supply truck, work, pay home, leave. 
Was it a scary prospect to leave the security of

17:17.000 --> 17:28.446
skiing traumatic? Was there a one time in 
particular that you remember that boy, I'm not

17:32.170 --> 17:33.973
looking forward to this summer at all. I just don't 
feel good, I don't have enough money, or I'm

17:34.033 --> 17:43.826
leaving this girl, or I'm... Yeah, you have to 
leave your friendship with these beautiful

17:34.033 --> 17:43.826
girls. There was one season, you know, the one that 
I met this gal from Sacramento,

17:43.846 --> 17:51.757
and... Who was that? Pardon? Who was that? The girl 
from Sacramento? The girl from Sacramento where

17:53.339 --> 17:56.924
Bill Klein told me not to get involved. Oh, yes, 
right. Any rich girls. Psychologist.

17:59.268 --> 17:59.528
Psychologist. No, that was in Pendley Hill. The 
psychology was in Pendley Hill. She was the one

18:02.718 --> 18:12.044
that was the advertising manager for the Thailand 
Country Shopping Center in Sacramento, a brand

18:02.718 --> 18:12.044
new shopping center. And she wrote a column. the 
shopping center column about people, that they

18:13.902 --> 18:22.970
still use today, that technique, which, of 
course, was totally new to me. This merchandising

18:23.531 --> 18:34.080
technique was my first introduction to business 
advertising, an American way of doing business. I

18:34.100 --> 18:36.443
found it fascinating. And she was crazy about this 
guy. She thought he was a genius. to do all these

18:41.307 --> 18:42.789
things. And of course, I'm sure he had two or three 
Cadillacs and was a big businessman in

18:42.889 --> 18:50.677
Sacramento. So that was a tough time. That was a 
tough season for him. You have to give up this

18:52.859 --> 19:05.813
entree by being able to get into this kind of 
business world that was so fascinating and

18:52.859 --> 19:05.813
rewarding, obviously, because they were all 
driving around in fancy cars, and I probably

19:06.232 --> 19:09.836
didn't even have a car. And you were dating already 
with her? Yeah, yeah, a few dates. But it's very

19:15.603 --> 19:21.830
hard to take them out when you don't have any money. 
There's certain things to be expected, dinner,

19:22.090 --> 19:26.956
movies. So you were pretty close, and you knew that 
when summer came, when May 1st came, you'd have to

19:26.976 --> 19:30.940
leave. and you would not see her again, unless she 
showed up for the next season. Yeah, pretty much

19:35.494 --> 19:37.115
so. And so it was pretty hard to, I mean, one assumed 
that once May 1st rolled around and you started

19:37.135 --> 19:46.524
your summer work, that she wouldn't wait around. 
Chances are you wouldn't see her again the next

19:47.605 --> 19:49.887
season. Which was correct, because she didn't get 
married to some wealthy guy from Milwaukee, dear

19:50.147 --> 19:56.012
family. How did you find that out? I did meet her. 
Either I called her or she called me, and... when I

20:01.750 --> 20:04.714
was on the peninsula. That surprised me. After 
she'd gotten married, she wanted to see me, wanted

20:05.595 --> 20:08.919
to know what I was doing. How long after that? Five 
years? That was amazing that she was interested

20:13.244 --> 20:18.670
enough to... I'm trying to think, honey. I 
remember we had lunch. We met for lunch up at...

20:29.915 --> 20:34.421
fish market up at North Shore, the beach in San 
Francisco, North Beach. I remember being late for

20:35.422 --> 20:38.467
lunch and I had to apologize. We had French bread 
and the famous lunch. You were married by that time

20:44.034 --> 20:45.356
or not? No. That must have been a scary thing to have 
someone call you out of the past because you have to

20:46.758 --> 20:52.646
stop and think, what did I tell her the first time? 
What have I done since then? Well, it was getting

20:53.727 --> 20:56.311
better. I was accumulating a better... I mean, I 
had more to tell now. I had a life that I could talk

21:03.196 --> 21:05.280
about. I had a job. I was doing interesting things 
myself. So it was actually, you know, every year it

21:09.827 --> 21:12.933
was getting better. It seemed like it wasn't, but 
it was. What were you doing at that time on the

21:17.603 --> 21:19.826
peninsula? I was estimating, so it had to be after 
Herb died, and I'd already moved to, because Herb

21:19.846 --> 21:46.463
was in East Bay, Oakland, and then I got a job with 
AMCO, which had a place in Oakland, but they also

21:19.846 --> 21:46.463
had a place on the peninsula, and they transferred 
me to the peninsula across the bay, and I moved into

21:19.846 --> 21:46.463
San Mateo, and...

21:47.675 --> 22:04.337
I left them for Clark Door,

21:47.675 --> 22:04.337
which was a cabinet and pre-hung door shop, 
similar to what Earl had, only more cabinets and

21:47.675 --> 22:04.337
things. And so I worked for these Clark boys. They 
had hired me away from somebody I had been a

22:09.460 --> 22:22.913
competitor of theirs and what I would do is I would 
go to my competitors and surprisingly they would

22:09.460 --> 22:22.913
offer me jobs because I was hurting them. Sure. So 
they would say, okay, why don't you bring over your

22:24.455 --> 22:27.598
clients to mine? We need the business. We'll give 
you $15 more. What are you making? And they would up

22:32.724 --> 22:40.172
my salary a little bit, and I would bring as many 
clients as I could over to the next guy. So when

22:40.533 --> 22:51.685
somebody was hassling me or they wanted to put the 
screws to me, then I would look for a competitor and

22:40.533 --> 22:51.685
take my clients with me. Is it hard for you to leave 
people?

22:56.928 --> 23:00.733
My friends, yes, but when they put the screws to me, 
no. And can you usually find a reason why they're

23:01.394 --> 23:06.280
putting the screws to you? What I'm curious about 
is, does the decision to leave come first, and then

23:08.342 --> 23:15.631
looking for a good reason, they're hassling me? 
Remember that time they said this and this and

23:16.432 --> 23:20.997
this, and then you create, you engineer a reason to 
leave you. Does the leaving come first, or does the

23:22.023 --> 23:25.109
hassling come first? The hassling comes first. 
Oh, okay. So you begin to feel that they really are

23:27.212 --> 23:32.001
down on you for some reason? You know how 
management is. You're talking about people that

23:36.710 --> 23:41.378
know very little more than you do, are in charge of 
you. Right. So I don't, you know, and I'm also in

23:42.380 --> 23:46.427
many... cases, as Gene finally pointed out to me, 
is that I'm usually a threat to them. I usually

23:52.420 --> 23:56.185
threaten my own managers. So in those days I was 
very outspoken, and I still am, which is not very

23:57.107 --> 24:03.555
smart. I'm not skilled in the corporate gameplay. 
I read books. I try to learn like Peter's Principle

24:10.967 --> 24:14.452
and things like that. I try to get away from my 
bluntness and use more diplomacy. And Jean helps

24:21.042 --> 24:24.567
me with that a lot. But it's hard for you to leave 
people, or it's not? It just depends on how they...

24:32.118 --> 24:34.722
I want to add a little something here. To... to me, 
he has very often said or expressed his attitude

24:36.239 --> 24:47.796
that if somebody does something like that to him, 
they don't exist anymore. And I've seen him do

24:47.816 --> 24:49.078
this. They simply do not exist. I have the same 
opinion. Yeah, I could, you know, they just died.

24:57.506 --> 24:58.127
Yeah. And so there have been a lot of times when 
maybe that influenced me, too. I didn't really

25:02.136 --> 25:10.032
think that that would happen to us, but that if I did 
hassle them too much, I would not exist. Right. and

25:10.192 --> 25:35.895
i thought then when finally we got down to that 
point where i was ready that was included what was

25:10.192 --> 25:35.895
going to happen i would walk out the door and i would 
no longer exist well that wouldn't exactly have

25:10.192 --> 25:35.895
happened but the impression is this all with 
